column10:
TL;DR Soulslike meets metroidvania

Wot I liked
- The protagonist does not speak much but is very expressive;
- It has a surprisingly deep for a roguelike combat, which is more soulslike: you got dodge, block, parry, ranged, melee, spells, pets, traps, bombs;
- Many weapons: melee, ranged, shields, spells, thrown - slow and fast with different moves and abilities;
- Very deep and customizable options (game's still very hard);
- You can reach some areas after gaining various movement abilities;
- The game is pretty hard on normal, then you can crank it up 5 times more hard;
- A bunch of Easter Eggs and pop culture references;
- There is a book promoting other indie roguelikes (I had to note that I had played most of them);
- Very stylistically cool DLC collabs with other IPs.

Wot I disliked
- You could say it's a bit pricey for an indie game, but it seems their team is quite big;
- The bane of all roguelites: your run can become prohibitively hard depending on your luck.

To sum it all up, Dead Cells has everything a soulslike metroidvania need and more. At first I just wanted to kill some boss and call it a day, but as I discoveered more mutations, spells and weapons I was more enticed to get to the end boss. Even though difficulties above Normal were too much for me, I respect the high skill ceiling.
